.TH LU\-MATCH 1 "2026-04-27" "logicutils 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lu\-match \- multi\-wildcard pattern matching with variable binding
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lu\-match
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fIPATTERN\fR [\fIINPUT\fR...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lu\-match
matches one or more inputs against a pattern containing named wildcards
and prints the resulting variable bindings. Unlike POSIX glob, the
pattern may contain several wildcards bound to distinct names; the
matcher uses backtracking unification to find an assignment that makes
the pattern equal to the input.

A pattern is a literal string in which any occurrence of
.B {NAME}
is a wildcard captured into the variable
.IR NAME .
By default a wildcard matches a single path segment (no
.B /
characters). The variant
.B {NAME:any}
matches any string including separators;
.B {NAME:segment}
is the explicit form of the default.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-glob
Treat
.I INPUT
as a directory and walk the filesystem, returning every file whose path
matches \fIPATTERN\fR.
.TP
.BI \-\-template= TMPL
After matching, expand
.I TMPL
using the captured bindings (using the same
.B {NAME}
syntax) and print the result instead of the bindings.
.TP
.BI \-\-filter= EXPR
Drop matches that do not satisfy \fIEXPR\fR (e.g.
.BR "X != Y" ).
.TP
.BI \-\-format= FORMAT
Output format: \fIplain\fR, \fIjson\fR, \fItsv\fR, \fIcsv\fR, \fItoml\fR,
\fIshell\fR. The
.I shell
format produces \fBNAME=VALUE\fR pairs suitable for
.BR eval .
.SH EXIT STATUS
0 if at least one match is produced, 1 if no match, 2 on error.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Bind two wildcards from a filename:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ lu\-match \(aqalign\-{X}\-{Y}.bam\(aq align\-sample1\-hg38.bam
X=sample1
Y=hg38
.fi
.RE
.PP
Walk the filesystem and emit derived target names:
.PP
.RS
.nf
lu\-match \-\-glob \-\-template=\(aqresults/{patient}\-{tissue}.bam\(aq \\\\
\(aqdata/{patient}\-{tissue}.fastq\(aq
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR lu\-expand (1),
.BR lu\-rule (1)
.SH AUTHOR
NEWSNIPER.
